Female: Brachypterous, rarely macropterous; length 4.1–5.3. COLORATION: Similar to male but often darker, sometimes uniformly dark brown to black except for paler posterior margin of evaporatorium, antennal segments I, III, and IV, rarely only posterior margin of evaporatorium area and antennal segments III and IV pale brown. SURFACE AND VESTITURE: As in male. STRUCTURE AND MEASUREMENTS: Body 2.2–3.1× as long as width of pronotum. Head: 1.2–1.3× as wide as high; vertex 2.4–3.1× as wide as eye; antennal segment II 1.0–1.2× as long as basal width of pronotum, 1.2–1.4× as long as width of head. Thorax: Pronotum with concave posterior margin, 1.9–2.1× as wide as long and 1.1–1.4× as wide as head; length of hemelytra in brachypterous females ranging from reaching middle of abdominal segment VII to covering entire abdomen, typically reaching middle of abdominal segment VIII, claval commissure as long as inner claval margin, posterior and lateral margins of hemelytra rounded, shape of hemelytra in macropterous females distinctly more oval than in male. GENITALIA: Sclerotized rings oval, with comparatively robust walls, medial sclerites distinctly curved, twin-coned, nearly equal in length to and distinctly more narrow than sclerotized ring (fig. 15); posterior wall of bursa copulatrix with trapeziform sclerite uniformly sclerotized, incision on the anterior margin narrow and not reaching middle of sclerite, anterior angles of this sclerite somewhat dentate, posterior margin without sclerites (as in fig. 18,
bivittatus
); vulva with curved sclerites forming a circle (as in fig. 19,
vittipennis
).
